summary: So I thought I’d show Mum - a massive Queen fan - a passage in Good Omens where Crowley is receiving orders from his Lord... and...
body:
So I thought I’d show Mum - a massive Queen fan - a passage in Good Omens where Crowley is receiving orders from his Lord… and now Mum is under the impression that in this universe Satan is Freddie Mercury..

I tried explaining “no, he’s not, Satan’s just using his voice” but I think she’s interested in finding out more purely based on this misinterpretation. 

So… success? XD

by NeverNooitNiet

It was stupid of him, though. And dangerous— he still had the little scorched spots from that time in the 1940s to prove it. But he’d slathered the scaly soles of his feet in sunscreen, and then wrapped that slippery mess in three pairs of thick hiking socks, before forcing that into his thickest-soled pair of boots, so he reckoned he’d be all right, for a little while, providing he didn’t touch anything. Or step on a saint, or something.

The world fails to end, and Crowley visits a cathedral.

summary: Someone called A Spokesman sounded close to hysteria. “. . . danger to employees or the public,” he was saying. “And precisely...
body:
Someone called A Spokesman sounded close to hysteria.

“… danger to employees or the public,” he was saying.

“And precisely how much nuclear material has escaped?” said the interviewer.

There was a pause. “We wouldn’t say escaped,” said the spokesman. “Not escaped. Temporarily mislaid.”

“You mean it is still on the premises?”

“We certainly cannot see how it could have been removed from them,” said the spokesman.

“Surely you have considered terrorist activity?”

There was another pause. Then the spokesman said, in the quiet tones of someone who has had enough and is going to quit after this and raise chickens somewhere, “Yes, I suppose we must. All we need to do is find some terrorists who are capable of taking an entire nuclear reactor out of its can while it’s running and without anyone noticing. It weighs about a thousand tons and is forty feet high. So they’ll be quite strong terrorists. Perhaps you’d like to ring them up, sir, and ask them questions in that supercilious, accusatory way of yours.”

“But you said the power station is still producing electricity,” gasped the interviewer.

“It is.”

“How can it still be doing that if it hasn’t got any reactors?”

You could see the spokesman’s mad grin, even on the radio. You could see his pen, poised over the “Farms for Sale” column in Poultry World. “We don’t know,” he said. “We were hoping you clever buggers at the BBC would have an idea.”

 - Neil Gaiman, Terry Pratchett, Good Omens

summary: I haven’t had a hold of my good omens copy for a good... almost 2 years now probably. I let a friend borrow it to read, then...
caption:
I haven’t had a hold of my good omens copy for a good… almost 2 years now probably. I let a friend borrow it to read, then they gave it to another friend to hold on to to give to me, but they kept forgetting to bring it with them so it just ended up in the hands of yet another friend who is interested in reading.

She was the one who sent me most of these!! A handful of old doodles and comments and highlights throughout the book. These are only the few she caught while skimming. She’ll probably send me more once she starts reading - but wow what a blast from the past huh. The lot of these are probably from back in 2015!

The book is full of highlights of things I either wanted to draw or just parts and dialogue I enjoyed. They are even color coded! I’m not sure what I was keeping track of with the index card though. Anyways, super nostalgic stuff <3

summary:
I feel like Good Omens is about Aziraphale and Crowley the same way Silence of the Lambs is about Hannibal Lecter.
Anthony...
body:
I feel like Good Omens is about Aziraphale and Crowley the same way Silence of the Lambs is about Hannibal Lecter.

Anthony Hopkins won best actor despite only being on screen for a set amount of time. Reading the book is the same. Some characters just have presence. They leave an impression on your mind/heart/soul.

The same can be said about Aziraphale and Crowley and their interactions in Good Omens. You enjoy the whole thing thoroughly and love all the characters but when you tell people about it you focus on the angel and the demon.

Some characters are more than words on paper and images in a mind’s eye.

Keep in mind I am biased: I reread either Hannibal or SotL almost yearly and Good Omens is my favourite book ever. But there are other examples and everyone has to have at least one of those.

Keep in mind I am biased: I reread either Hannibal or SotL almost yearly and Good Omens is my favourite book ever. But there are other examples and everyone has to have at least one of those.
